Keywords : breast cancer , homologous <termsem="GO:0006310"> recombination </term> .
BRCA2 was the second breast cancer susceptibility gene to be discovered , and was isolated through positional cloning using data from families with inherited breast cancer [ 4 ] .
Cells with mutant BRCA2 protein are , like many cancer cells , genetically unstable and accumulate gross chromosomal rearrangements [ 5,6 ] .
The sequence of this large protein ( 3418 amino acids ) offers very little clue to its function , although there are eight repeated segments ( termed BRC repeats ) in the middle of the protein that are highly conserved among mammalian orthologs [ 7,8 ] .
